% ===== Page 2 =====
Suppose $\mathbf{k}$ is graphical. What is $N(n,\mathbf{k})$? It is a difficult counting problem (1958 - ...); a nice review of its history/progress can be found in N. Wormald, ``\emph{Asymptotic enumeration of graphs with a given degree sequence}'', Proc. ICM, 2018.

Why the problem is hard? Observe:
\begin{equation}
N(n,\mathbf{k}) = \frac{N_p}{N_s}\mathcal{P}, \text{ where}
\tag{9.2}
\end{equation}

\begin{itemize}
\item $N_p = \frac{(2m)!}{m!2^m} = (2m-1)!! \, (n!! = n(n-2)(n-4)\ldots 2(1))$ is the number of pairings of $2m$ stubs (half-edges), indeed:

\begin{itemize}
\item $2m!$ the number of permutations of $2m$ elements,
\item $m!$ the number of orderings of pairs in the row,
\item $2^m$ is the number of orderings of the elements in the pairs;
\end{itemize}

\item $N_s = \prod_{i=1}^n k_i!$ is the number of different pairings that lead to the same graph;

\item $\mathcal{P}$ is the probability that a random pairing leads to a simple graph.
\end{itemize}

Note:

\begin{itemize}
\item Estimating $\mathcal{P}$ is the main difficulty.

\item Results are only of asymptotic nature under different assumptions.

\item For power-law sequences, rigorous results are available only for $\gamma > \frac{5}{2}$ (Gao, Wormald, 2016).

\item Non-rigorous arguments suggest they hold for smaller $\gamma$ as well (Bianconi et al, 2008).

\item Bender, Canfield, 1978:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P} \approx \exp\left[-\frac{1}{4}\left(\left(\frac{\langle k^2\rangle}{\langle k\rangle}\right)^2 - 1\right)\right],
\tag{9.3}
\end{equation}

where $\langle k^2\rangle = \sum k_i^2/n$, $\langle k\rangle = \sum k_i/n$.
\end{itemize}

Test question: how are you supposed to interpret the `$\approx$' sign in the last equation?

\newpage

% ===== Page 3 =====
\subsubsection*{9.1.2 \quad Generation}

The graph generation is also difficult. Test question: why?

\textbf{Classes of approaches to graph generation in CM:}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Random stub pairing and rejection if a multigraph is formed}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item No rejection if it is a CM of multigraphs.
        \item Prob[simple graph]$\to 0$ if $\langle k^2 \rangle \to \infty$ (Janson, 2009).
        \item The fraction of multiedges and self-loops is negligible (even if $\langle k^2 \rangle \to \infty$) ``for many purposes'' (van der Hofstad et al) $\Rightarrow$
    \end{itemize}
    
    \item \textbf{Random stub pairing and erasure of multiedges and self-loops}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item A.k.a. the \textit{erased configuration model} (ECM).
        \item The resulting degree sequence is different from $\mathbf{k}$, but the difference is negligible ``for many purposes''.
    \end{itemize}
    
    \item \textbf{Start with any graph with the required degree sequence and then swap edges randomly like this:}
    
    \begin{center}
    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
        % Left graph
        \node[circle,fill,inner sep=2pt,label=above:$k_1$] (k1) at (0,1) {};
        \node[circle,fill,inner sep=2pt,label=below:$k_2$] (k2) at (0,-1) {};
        \node[circle,fill,inner sep=2pt,label=above:$k_3$] (k3) at (2,1) {};
        \node[circle,fill,inner sep=2pt,label=below:$k_4$] (k4) at (2,-1) {};
        \draw (k1) -- (k2);
        \draw (k3) -- (k4);
        
        % Arrow
        \node at (3.5,0) {$\Rightarrow$};
        
        % Right graph
        \node[circle,fill,inner sep=2pt,label=above:$k_1$] (k1r) at (5,1) {};
        \node[circle,fill,inner sep=2pt,label=below:$k_2$] (k2r) at (5,-1) {};
        \node[circle,fill,inner sep=2pt,label=above:$k_3$] (k3r) at (7,1) {};
        \node[circle,fill,inner sep=2pt,label=below:$k_4$] (k4r) at (7,-1) {};
        \draw (k1r) -- (k4r);
        \draw (k3r) -- (k2r);
    \end{tikzpicture}
    \end{center}
    
    \begin{itemize}
        \item If done properly(!), after $O(m)$ swaps this Markov process is properly mixed (P. Erdős, Z. Toroczkai, K. Bassler, A. Coolen).
        \item The graph to start with can be generated using the \textit{Havel--Hakimi algorithm}, which iteratively connects the highest-degree node to other nodes with highest-possible degrees:
        \begin{enumerate}[(a)]
            \item let a nonincreasing $\mathbf{k} = \{k_i\}_{i=1}^n = \{s, t_1, \ldots, t_s, k_1, \ldots, k_{n-s-1}\}$ be the numbers of unmatched stubs attached to nodes $i = 1, 2, \ldots, n$;
            \item match the $s$ stubs of node 1 with 1 stub of each of the nodes $2, \ldots, s+1$;
            \item observe that the sequence of numbers of unmatched stubs becomes $\mathbf{k}' = \{0, t_1 - 1, \ldots, t_s - 1, k_1, \ldots, k_{n-s-1}\}$;
            \item remove the first element (0) from $\mathbf{k}'$, and rearrange it so that it becomes nonincreasing;
            \item go to step (a) with $n$ replaced by $n-1$.
        \end{enumerate}
    \end{itemize}
    
    \item \textbf{Advanced algorithms}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textit{Del Genio et al, PLOS ONE, 2010}
        \begin{itemize}
            \item[--] Does not sample graph uniformly but reports weights; the worst-case running time is $O(nm)$ for any graphical degree sequence.
        \end{itemize}
        \item \textit{Arman, Gao, Wormald, FOCS, 2019}
        \begin{itemize}
            \item[--] Samples graphs uniformly, but the running time is proven to be:
            \begin{itemize}
                \item[*] $O(m)$ if $k_{\max}^4 = O(m)$ \\
                (for power-law $\mathbf{k}$'s, this means that $\gamma > 5$),
                \item[*] $O(n)$ if $\mathbf{k}$ is a power law with $\gamma > \frac{21+\sqrt{61}}{10} \approx 2.88$.
            \end{itemize}
            \item[--] Random pairing followed by sophisticated corrections.
            \item[--] This seems to be the state of the art at this moment.
        \end{itemize}
    \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

