% ===== Page 5 =====
\subsubsection{Generation}

Given $\mathbf{k} = \{k_i\}$:

1. solve Eq.~(9.7) for $\{\lambda_i\}_{i=1}^n$,

2. connect nodes $i$ and $j$ with probability $p_{ij}$ in Eq.~(9.6) for $i < j = 1, 2, ..., n$.

\subsubsection{Classical limit approximation (Chung-Lu model)}

Why ``classical'': in statistical physics, Eq.~(9.6) gives the expected number of particles in state $\{i, j\}$ in quantum Fermi gases. The corresponding analogy of this section is the \emph{classical} (vs. quantum) ideal gas.

\paragraph{Definition}

Observe that if $p_{ij} \ll 1 \iff e^{\lambda_i + \lambda_j} \gg 1$ (but also ``in many other cases'' (Janson, 2010)), then
\begin{align*}
p_{ij} &= \frac{1}{e^{\lambda_i + \lambda_j} + 1} \approx e^{-\lambda_i} e^{-\lambda_j} \Rightarrow \\
k_i &= \sum_{j=1}^n p_{ij} = e^{-\lambda_i} \sum_{j=1}^n e^{-\lambda_j} = c e^{-\lambda_i} \Rightarrow \\
\sum_{i=1}^n k_i &= kn = c^2 \Rightarrow \\
e^{-\lambda_i} &= \frac{k_i}{\sqrt{kn}} \Rightarrow \\
p_{ij} &\approx \boxed{p_{ij}^{\text{CL}} = \min\left(1, \frac{k_i k_j}{kn}\right)},
\end{align*}
\begin{equation}
(9.8)
\end{equation}

where $\bar{k} = \sum_{i=1}^n k_i / n$.

\paragraph{Generation}

Given $\mathbf{k} = \{k_i\}$, connect nodes $i$ and $j$ with probability $p_{ij}^{\text{CL}}$ in Eq.~(9.8) for $i < j = 1, 2, ..., n$.

