% ===== Page 6 =====
\section{Hypersoft configuration model $\text{HSCM}(n,\rho)$}

Degree sequences in real networks are rarely fixed since networks are dynamic, but the degree distribution often stays the same for decades (e.g., in the Internet).

\subsection{Definition}

\textbf{Definition 9.6.} The $\text{HSCM}(n,\rho)$ is the $\text{HSCM}(n,\mathbf{k})$, where $\mathbf{k} \sim \rho$, and $\rho$ is a fixed joint distribution.

\textbf{Notes:}

\begin{itemize}
\item Usually, $\rho(\mathbf{k}) = \prod_i \rho(k_i)$ (i.e., $\rho_{\mathbf{k}} = \rho_k^n$ or $k_i \stackrel{i.i.d.}{\sim} \rho$), which is the settings in this section, i.e.,

\item Henceforth, distribution $\rho$ is $\rho(k_i)$: $\{k_i\}$ are independent samples from a fixed distribution (e.g., Pareto).

\item The proof of unbiasedness of the HSCM in these settings appeared only recently and only for Pareto $\rho$ (van der Hoorn et al., 2018).

\item In the HSCM, both the degree distribution and the degree sequence distribution converge to the $\rho$-mixed Poisson (as opposed to HER $\mathcal{G}(n,\rho)$).

\item If $\rho$ is Pareto, then the $\rho$-mixed Poisson is a power law (HW).

\item If $\rho = \text{Pareto}[k, \gamma = 3]$, then the $\text{HSCM}(n,\rho)$ is equivalent to the soft preferential attachment (SPA) model.

\item In SPA, new nodes connect to existing nodes with probability proportional to their \emph{expected} (vs. actual) degrees.

\item SPA is thus the unbiased model of random graphs with a power-law degree distribution with $\gamma = 3$.

\item But SPA $\neq$ PA.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Generation}

\textbf{Option 1}

The basic option is to generate graphs as in $\text{SCM}(n,\mathbf{k})$ with random $\mathbf{k}$:

1. sample $k_i \stackrel{i.i.d.}{\sim} \rho$, and

2. generate $G \sim \text{SCM}(n,\mathbf{k})$.

The main difficulty is that you have to solve (9.7) for each $G$.

\textbf{Option 2}

Observe that Eq. (9.7) can be used to derive $\rho(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ from $\rho(\mathbf{k})$, so, as soon as such a derivation is complete,

1. sample $\boldsymbol{\lambda} \sim \rho(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$,

2. connect $i$ and $j$ with probability $p_{ij}$ in Eq. (9.6).

In general, the derivation of $\rho(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ from $\rho(\mathbf{k})$ may be difficult to carry out. Luckily, if $\{k_i\}$ are independent Paretos, then we have the following results.

\vspace{1em}
